:0;list-style-type:decimal"><li><i>The Kelce chronicles</i>: Back in the sp=
ring, soon after <b>Jason Kelce </b>retired following a 13-year career with=
 the Philadelphia Eagles, his reps opened talks with each of the NFL=E2=80=
=99s TV partners: Amazon, CBS, ESPN, Fox, and NBC. Not surprisingly, they a=
ll showed initial interest. He=E2=80=99s personable, he=E2=80=99s good on T=
V, and over the course of his career, he=E2=80=99s been a reliable go-to qu=
ote for the beat writers. Oh, and his brother happens to be dating the most=
 famous woman on the planet.<br/><br/>During the process, it became apparen=
t that the offensive lineman was interested in more than just becoming <i>a=
nother </i>talking head. After all, he and <b>Travis</b> had just cut a $10=
0 million podcast deal with Wondery for
<i>New Heights</i>, and their mother=E2=80=99s Chiefs-Eagles Super Bowl-era=
 Campbell=E2=80=99s Soup ads offered them a taste of commercial resonance. =
Kelce told the execs that he wanted to host his own late-night show=E2=80=
=94complete with a brass band. Network executives were leery about committi=
ng to a TV show with someone who had zero television experience, but he is =
a Kelce, so they all showed interest.<br/><br/>ESPN wound up signing Kelce =
for around $8 million per year, per several sources. (On Thursday, I cited =
reports that put his salary at under $2 million and was bombarded by texts =
with the real number. Thanks, guys.) The ESPN deal centers on Kelce=E2=80=
=99s contribution to the <i>MNF </i>studio show, but the network will honor=
 his late-night request by broadcasting five episodes=E2=80=94produced by N=
FL Films, as I also noted last week=E2=80=94on consecutive Friday nights at=
 1 a.m. ET in January. A five-episode run will presumably give ESPN execs e=
nough of a chance to decide if they want to move
forward with it or not. No word yet on the brass band.<br/><br/></li><li><i=
>Is =E2=80=9Cshared reality=E2=80=9D really a thing?</i>: People have been =
bugging me to write about this relatively new company called Cosm for the b=
etter part of a year, but I=E2=80=99ve resisted. Cosm is essentially a virt=
ual experiences company that creates a sort of miniature version of the The=
 Sphere for fans, who watch a huge video screen (87-foot by 55-foot) that o=
ffers unimaginable views of the actions=E2=80=94the World Series from behin=
d home plate or an NFL game from the line of scrimmage, etcetera. The compa=
ny has two facilities in the U.S.=E2=80=94one in Hollywood Park, another ou=
tside of Dallas, and yet another forthcoming in Atlanta=E2=80=94and it is t=
urning customers into evangelists. This morning, the NFL announced a deal t=
hat allows Cosm to carry all of the league=E2=80=99s primetime games (Thurs=
day, Sunday, and Monday night), plus some additional Fox games through the =
end of this season. <br/><br/>Despite its momentum, some
of my sources worry about the business plan=E2=80=94the capex required, the=
 scale challenges (the L.A. facility has 700 seats), etcetera=E2=80=94and t=
he entire gimmicky shtick. At what point will fans encounter a similar expe=
rience through a headset? Or will the NFL eventually sanction its own exper=
ience? Anyway, not a lot of moats=E2=80=A6<br/><br/></li><li><i>Smoltz=E2=
=80=99s NFL influences</i>: When I asked John Smoltz about the announcers t=
hat he tried to emulate, I was surprised that the baseball Hall of Famer im=
mediately cited NFL analysts like <b>Troy</b> <b>Aikman</b> and <b>Cris</b>=
 <b>Collinsworth</b>. =E2=80=9CTroy Aikman explains things without dumbing =
it down,=E2=80=9D Smoltz said. =E2=80=9CJust because he played the sport, h=
e could spit out all kinds of coverages and terms that nobody would know an=
ything about. I want to be able to do that as a baseball broadcaster [for] =
everyone, from people who are tuning in for the first time, to an expert. A=
nd that=E2=80=99s a fine needle to thread.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Early in
his broadcasting career, Smoltz would try to use as many stats as he could.=
 Now, he shelves those stats in favor of telling stories. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m looking for moments that I lived. I don=E2=80=99t think there=E2=80=99=
s a moment in the game that I would be surprised could happen.=E2=80=9D Smo=
ltz made that comment <i>before</i> <b>Freddie</b> <b>Freeman</b> hit the f=
irst walk-off grand slam in World Series history.<br/><br/></li><li><i>MLB =
Network 15 years on</i>: Loyal Varsity readers know how cord-cutting has ra=
vaged league-owned networks like MLB Network, which is currently in a littl=
e more than 30 million homes. But the business has pivoted during the past =
decade-plus from a focus on the channel, itself, to serving MLB=E2=80=99s b=
roader distribution needs. During the 2009 Yankees-Phillies World Series, t=
he network had 35 people at Yankee Stadium producing <i>MLB Tonight</i>. Fo=
r tonight=E2=80=99s Yankees-Dodgers game, there will be 200 staffers at the=
 stadium, producing five studio shows. <br/><br/>In that
