         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s2">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">DirecTV=E2=80=99s <=
b>Rob</b> <b>Thun</b> addressed this phenomenon at the L.A. Sports Council=
=E2=80=99s annual conference earlier this month. Since its launch in the mi=
d-1990s, DirecTV has marketed itself as a leader in sports TV. In the last =
few years, however, the satellite distributor has lost NFL Sunday Ticket ri=
ghts and had a very public battle with Disney during which ESPN went dark o=
n the service for nearly two weeks. A year earlier, Disney and ESPN went da=
rk on Charter for about the same amount of time.<br/><br/>ESPN clearly stil=
l holds most of the leverage in these battles=E2=80=94no distributor wants =
to lose its college football and NFL offerings every weekend. But it=E2=80=
=99s also clear that distribution executives recognize how much ESPN relies=
 on its affiliate fees to underwrite its transformation into a legit stream=
er. =E2=80=9CThe pay TV model still has to have a
level of subsidization in order for the content providers to have some cert=
ainty and actually to make the investments in the programming they make,=E2=
=80=9D Thun explained onstage at the conference, articulating the distribut=
or=E2=80=99s negotiating angle.<br/><br/>Thun said the fight with Disney hi=
nged on whether DirecTV would be given the flexibility to offer genre-speci=
fic skinny bundles, like sports, kids, and news=E2=80=94their own Venu-styl=
e counterattack to offer consumers more affordable affinity-based packages =
rather than bloated bundles. =E2=80=9CWe over-index a little bit in sports =
fans,=E2=80=9D Thun said. =E2=80=9CAnd we have people who are casual sports=
 fans who will watch a game of big interest like the Super Bowl. But there =
are plenty of customers who don=E2=80=99t watch sports whatsoever. And that=
=E2=80=99s part of what we=E2=80=99re trying to unlock for customers.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>ESPN=E2=80=99s model, of course, rests on the hypothesis that =
a large pure-play sports streamer=E2=80=94the product known in Bristol as
=E2=80=9CFlagship=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94will enter the world with product-market=
 fit. And yet, investment analysts at MoffettNathanson scrutinized this ass=
umption in a recent report, which underscored the difficulty of building pr=
ofitable streaming businesses with sports. Sure, sports can bring in new su=
bscribers, but we have yet to see a sports strategy that can yield signific=
ant <i>profits</i> from streaming. After all, the rights fees are enormous,=
 the production costs are formidable, the churn is seasonal, the tech stack=
 is extendable but expensive, and the content, itself, is live and therefor=
e ephemeral. =E2=80=9CAll of this,=E2=80=9D MoffettNathanson writes=E2=80=
=94=E2=80=9Cthe impact of ESPN Flagship, whether Venu still plans to launch=
, the future of Disney+ and Hulu either as standalone or integrated service=
s, bundles and unbundling=E2=80=94leads to the key question at the heart of=
 investor concerns: what are Disney=E2=80=99s long-term streaming margins?=
=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
